+--------------------------------------------------------------------+
| Time Warner Cable Implements Packet Shaping                        |
|   from the neutral-networks-breath-easy dept.                      |
|   posted by Zonk on Sunday June 10, @05:07 (Networking)            |
|   http://slashdot.org/article.pl?sid=07/06/10/0645232              |
+--------------------------------------------------------------------+

[0]RFC writes "In a move that may be indicative of modern ISP customer
service, Time Warner has announced [1]the introduction of packet shaping
technology to its network. 'Packet shaping technology has been
implemented for newsgroup applications, regardless of the provider, and
all peer-to-peer networks and certain other high bandwidth applications
not necessarily limited to audio, video, and voice over IP telephony.' As
the poster observes, this essentially renders premium service useless.
The company is already warning users that attempts to circumvent these
measures is a violation of their Terms of Service."

Discuss this story at:
    http://slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=07/06/10/0645232

Links:
    0. http://michkol.webd.pl/rfc/
    1. http://www.dslreports.com/forum/remark,18468495


+--------------------------------------------------------------------+
| Justice Dept. Defends Microsoft Against Google                     |
|   from the friends-in-high-places dept.                            |
|   posted by Zonk on Sunday June 10, @07:06 (Microsoft)             |
|   http://politics.slashdot.org/article.pl?sid=07/06/10/0622249     |
+--------------------------------------------------------------------+

[0]Frosty Piss writes "The Seattle PI reports that [1]Google has
complained to US antitrust officials about the hard-drive searching tool
built into Windows Vista, saying that it stymies Google's similar search
program. The complaint, lodged late last year, was revealed Saturday by
The New York Times in a story about [2]the Bush administration's handling
of Microsoft antitrust issues. The real story, though, is not the Google
complaint itself, but how the Justice Department is failing to enforce
the Microsoft anti-trust decree. According to the story, Thomas Barnett,
the assistant U.S. attorney general in charge of antitrust issues, sent a
memo last month to state attorneys general across the nation, seeking to
persuade them to reject Google's complaint."

Discuss this story at:
    http://politics.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=07/06/10/0622249

Links:
    0. http://nojailforpot.com/
    1. http://seattlepi.nwsource.com/business/319231_msftgoogle09ww.html
    2. http://www.nytimes.com/2007/06/10/business/10microsoft.html?_r=1&hp&oref=slogin


